tooltipList.forEach((tooltip, index) => { // Adjust the regex to match searchString potentially surrounded by “ and followed by optional punctuation let regex = new RegExp(`(?<=\\b|\\s|^|“)${tooltip.searchString}(?=[.,;!?]?\\b|\\s|”|$)`, 'g'); let match; while ((match = regex.exec(str)) !== null) { matches.push({ start: match.index + (match[0].startsWith('“') ? 1 : 0), // Adjust for potential starting “ end: match.index + match[0].length - (match[0].endsWith('”') ? 1 : 0) - (match[2] ? 1 : 0), tooltipIndex: index }); } }); // Sort by starting position; if two start at the same position, longer match comes first matches.sort((a, b) => a.start - b.start || b.end - b.start - (a.end - a.start)); // Filter out overlaps for (let i = 0; i < matches.length - 1; ) { if (matches[i + 1].start < matches[i].end) { matches.splice(i + 1, 1); // Remove the next match since it overlaps } else { i++; // Move to next match } } return matches; } function applyTooltips(str) { const matches = getTooltips(str); let result = ''; let lastIndex = 0; matches.forEach(match => { const tooltip = tooltipList[match.tooltipIndex]; result += str.slice(lastIndex, match.start); result += `${tooltip.searchString}${tooltip.explanationText}`; lastIndex = match.end; }); result += str.slice(lastIndex); // Add the remainder of the original string return result; } function applyTooltipsToObject(obj) { for (let key in obj) { if (typeof obj[key] === 'string') { obj[key] = applyTooltips(obj[key]); } else if (typeof obj[key] === 'object') { applyTooltipsToObject(obj[key]); // Recursive call } } } applyTooltipsToObject(campaignTrail_temp.questions_json); applyTooltipsToObject(campaignTrail_temp.answers_json); Major Anderson and Lieutenant Morgan marched down darkened White House halls. The curtains were drawn all across the building. Dim emergency lights were the only thing that marked their progress through the desolate building.

“How long are we—.” Mayor Anderson began.

“However long it takes, I guess.” said Lieutenant Morgan. There was no one else around but still he whispered like a man in a library. It was important that they be aware of their surroundings. Each day, sounds of violence seemed to get closer to the building.

“But what’s ‘it’? Are we talking until he schedules elections? Until the Army can put them down?” Anderson saw the pale, ghostly portrait of James Buchanan floating in the darkness and felt a chill go down his spine. He willed himself to look away. “What is it that we’re even—.”

Morgan’s hand shot out and grabbed the younger man by the chest. Anderson’s heart leapt. The words died on his lips. He felt certain the crisis had finally arrived home, that the anarchists had finally snuck their way into the building after weeks of rioting, that they were about to hear the whistling of a bomb dropped by an Air Force that had finally decided to cut its losses, that the Soviets were launching an attack. Instead, he followed Anderson’s gaze.

At the end of the long, dark hallway was the dim light of a flashlight. And the man carrying it—.

“No,” gasped Anderson, almost without thinking. Morgan tightened his grip. A signal to shut up.

“You know, Jack. I suppose it was fitting that we have our own crises. You, Cuba. Me, the insurrectionists. Two sides of the same coin. What was it that you said?”

Anderson stared as the commander-in-chief spoke to a portrait on the wall. It was almost casual, the way the old man spoke, as if he were addressing an old friend.

“‘Deliberate deception and offensive threats.’ That’s what we’re dealing with now. Only it’s not outside anymore. It’s inside. It’s contaminated us. Like a goddamn disease. And we can’t let it go unchecked. No no no no. I won’t be a Chamberlain for the anarchists, I won’t.”

Something glinted in the darkness. Anderson saw the president press a bottle to his lips and then give a sigh of relief.

“Al didn’t understand that. That’s why he left, why he betrayed us. He didn’t have what it took, but you and I do. We understand that you can’t just let the enemy win. You have to fight back. You have to show the sons of bitches their place. Even if it costs you everything.”

Another swig from the bottle.

“I suppose that’s why they took you away.”

The hallway fell silent. The president swayed on his feet, looking strange and spectral, like a creature from a bygone era. Then, as if the portrait had dismissed him, the president shook his head. He turned on his feet and walked back down the long hallway he’d come from. Anderson and Morgan watched until the president disappeared into blackness. The portrait of John F. Kennedy, on the wall, remained.

In the far-off distance, they heard the encroaching rumble of gunfire.

Red Detachment of Women

They had been waiting since four in the morning.

The younger officer grew impatient, tapping his feet on the hard wood floors, fidgeting with one of the buttons on his uniform. It was newly pressed and cleaned. He had been anticipating this day for months. He just didn’t think he’d be the one to do it. Surely his more intelligent and disciplined peers would be the men called upon for such a duty. But the order was as clear as it could be. He would be the man to deliver the news, along with his elder counterpart, of course.

Graying at the temples, the older man’s uniform was rumpled, creased and wrinkled from years of use. But wit and ingenuity never ceased. He had witnessed horrors beyond his comprehension. He had held men bleeding out in his own arms. He had stared death in the eye on the battlefield and lived to tell the tale. And now here he was, in a shabby room cocooned within a vast building constructed just three years ago for a single guest. The elder man maintained a sense of playfulness in spite of it all, but even his patience was wearing thin.

Then it struck him.

A broad grin spreading across his face, the elder man motioned at his younger counterpart to move closer. The youthful man leaned in and the elder whispered, “陈，跟我来”

“跟着你去哪儿？你是什么意思？” the younger man asked.

你会发现的。快来,” the older man pointed towards the door, “上楼梯”

The younger man shook his head. “好吧,” he sighed, “至少比在这里等待要好”

The two men began to climb. The younger officer would crane his neck, trying to get a glimpse of life on the other floors, but there was none. Only dusty boxes that appeared like they had been there for years. What was this strange place? Sure, he knew the circumstances of the guest’s arrival, everyone in Beijing did. The entire world heard about it. He even understood why this guest was in such a place, given all he did for the People’s Republic, and how he disgraced the imperialist dogs who commanded him. But the guest had never once appeared in public while he was here. Surely he knew of all the rumors that swirled. But not once did he seek to correct them, instead he hid from the people inside his winding tower.

“停止,” the older man called out. The younger man stumbled. He had been distracted and didn’t even notice the massive wooden doors now before them. And what was that noise coming from behind them? Was there someone else in there the guest was talking to? Or is that…crying?

The elder man rapped his knuckles on the doors twice and the noise stopped.

“哦，等等。” the elder man whispered, fumbling for a small piece of paper in his pocket, when suddenly the doors swung open. The youthful man could not suppress a gasp.

Here sat Richard Nixon, yankee pig, sitting next to the roaring fireplace during a sweltering heat wave. It was not the fact that this man was in seclusion in Beijing that shocked the youthful man, but how this most important political exile looked. Anticipating his comeback, the older Marshal simply shrugged, and checked his watch, then peered around the corner.

“Come to think of it…” he added before trailing off. The younger man knew where this was going.

“Just lead the way.”

The two men milled through the halls, descending staircases and slinking through side entrances the younger one never knew existed, traversing the dimly lit fluorescent halls, before finally stopping at a wooden door, surrounded with yellowed peeling tile. “Gross, I just got th-”

The Marshals heard sprinting down the hall, and they darted back, watching two other guards rush into the room.

“You aren’t supposed to be in here!” one shouted.

Blue Moon

“I’m surprised the folks here aren’t still skipping down the halls”

Major Anderson waved off his younger briefer. “They’re not that type. They want to get right back to work. Or at least what’s that they say.”

“Those hippies outside wouldn’t know a thing about that,” muttered Lieutenant Morgan. “There were only a handful when I walked in. Weren’t even saying anything, just laying on the ground. One of those ‘die-ins.’”

Major Anderson shook his head before checking his watch. The younger man’s foot rapped against the carpet.

“Is it usual for these to start so late? Maybe they’re all just ‘busy at work,’ like you said, but this is important. There’s guys sitting on the runway at Guam waiting for his sign-off. We’ve already gotten State’s approval, so what’s the hold-up?”

The older man shook his head. "Oh, he's not in the Oval. He's talking. He's talking to..." His eyes became distant and glassy. After a moment lost in thought, the man sighed. "No escaping it. Why don't I just show you?"

The two officers milled through the sparse White House halls. Most younger staffers worked out of EOB, the holidays were in full swing, and it was now late into the evening when most high-level appointees had gone home. Only the Secret Service were visible. Ascending several flights of stairs and navigating through the darkened, narrow hallways, the young man felt winded finding his way around the labyrinthian building.

“I thought you said we would see him?” the younger man complained.

“I know, I know, I thought…” the elder officer’s voice trailed off. “Forget it, I guess he’s not here.”

“Good one, sir,” the younger officer grunted in barely concealed frustration.

As the pair slunk back to that same cramped office to wait for their briefing, the president could not hear them from inside the cocoon of the Oval Office. As he always did before major speeches, he sealed himself in a room for days, isolated from the rest of the world, blaring Richard Rodgers’ showtunes. His favorite, the president would tell his closest confidantes, was Victory at Sea. On the eve of his greatest triumphs, the president closed his eyes and listened, as if he were back on the warships he had gambled away his last few dollars on. If he concentrated hard enough, Richard Nixon could almost hear the waves crashing beneath his feet.

But there were no more speeches to write, no more Democrats to vanquish, no more wars to win. The fire inside him, that had strengthened his resolve through the worst hardships of his life, was now simmering. The next four years paralyzed Dick. He had to live up to expectations no other president could reach. The hopes and fears of an ungrateful nation that had finally let him into the company of Roosevelt, Jefferson, and Lincoln. But one still remained out of reach.

He never had to live up to this, Nixon thought with a grimace.

He never had to end the wars he started. He never had to reckon with the movements he ignored. He never had to pay off the expenses he piled up.

The fire rose. Nixon’s grip on the arms of his chair tightened. The very thought of that man rendered Dick speechless, the flames choking him on his own words. Dick could not even utter his name. His allies liked to think it was rage at that entire bastard family for how they swindled the country. But it was something different. When Nixon thought of that smug prick’s perfect hair and his million-dollar grin, the fire grew higher. Nixon had injured himself opening a car door the same day that man had finished an afternoon of sailing, a tennis match with his aides, and then smiled his way to the presidency at the debates.

He had never done a goddamned thing to earn the nation’s love. To earn Dick’s. The only thing that placed him above all other presidents was the bullet to his head.

If he had only been a few inches to the left, Nixon thought, the country would have learned how worthless that grin really was. Dick had learned from experience. He thought back to that train ride so many years ago, snaking through Western Pennsylvania, when Dick spent the night with him. When Dick first felt the fire. He had been impressed by that Brahmin too, flushing bright red when that man asked Dick who had tailored the suit he had bought at a Washington department store. Before Dick could answer, that man flashed a grin, placing a hand on Dick’s shoulder, telling him he was only joking, and that the cheap suit this Boston blue-blood was wearing had also been bought off-the-rack.

From that moment on, they were up all night, spending the train ride swapping war stories and probing each other’s weaknesses. For a moment, Dick thought, it almost seemed like he had found a friend, perhaps more. Perhaps a political ally, one to keep close as both men shot through the ranks of their parties, both gaining on their respective presidential nominations. Perhaps this man was the answer to the flames coursing through Dick. A childish fantasy, Dick thought now, to imagine he would have ever gotten close to Jack.

Dick wiped the tears from his face, laughing, remembering how his mother would scold him for crying so often. At Arthur’s side, by Harold’s bed, inside the walls of his New York penthouse surrounded by ancient Chinese art as the news poured in from Dallas. The fire reached his eyes.

Dick pushed himself away from his desk, feeling dizzy now, and opened the drawer. Taking the piece of cold steel out, Dick gazed up at the moon once more, remembering what Kennedy had said years ago. Nixon had shaken the hands of the men who walked on the lunar surface. He had turned those empty words into action. He had been given a greater achievement than any man in the nation’s history. He had fulfilled the dream. Now he had to take his final bow, and ascend to that pantheon, the one only Jack was at. Dick took one last look before the fire consumed him.

The elder man held his hand up and turned around to make a soft shhh noise. Peering around the corner of the hallway, the Major quickly pulled back, looking at the Lieutenant and mouthing “back there.” The Lieutenant swallowed inched around the corner to get a look for himself.

“We had the bastards on the run, I tell you. They just wouldn’t let us take our gloves off, get into the arena. Goddamn spineless sons-of-bitches.”

The president paced back and forth, nursing a bottle of brandy, but never treading far. His gaze rarely met the man he was speaking to, instead fixating downward, his eyes beady.

“It wasn’t like this back with the Senate…back with, heh, Christ, back with that damned Kahagan Douglas. We went after her. We didn’t pull our punches. We acted like real men. You gotta be strong. Have to be tough. Told them she was pink right down to her underwear. You remember that, don’t you?”

Silence.

“Of course you do. You saw it, we all saw it. You can’t hesitate in these things. Right when it gets narrow, gets down to the wire…that’s when they’ll come for you. They always do. The jackals in the press, the wolves gnawing at the gates, the beast around the corner…they lurk, waiting for their chance…”

His voice was raspy, perhaps it was the drinking, or perhaps he had already gotten hoarse from the past few days. But he had had this conversation before.

“That’s when I failed. When they started hitting me on the Hughes loan, the silly shit with…with Don, with—. Christ, trying to tear me down over some goddamn tenant agreement? But no, no. That wasn’t what did me in then. You remember it. It was the goddamn Cuba business. You did it, Jack.”

His portrait loomed, hung up high upon the wall, already larger than life, John F. Kennedy was forever immortalized on enormous canvas. His head held low, his arms crossed, deep in thought. Always at the ready for late-night ruminations with the current White House occupant.

“At the debate, it wasn’t the damned television camera or my knee from that trip in Alaska. It was you. You knew about what we were planning, with the Cubans, down in Central America, Miami, wherever it was. Every candidate would be briefed on something like that. But Ike, the son-of-a-bitch, kept telling us it wasn’t ready. Christ, it never was. But you didn’t give a damn about any of that. You accused me of being soft on the communists, not preparing for an attack in the Caribbean…and that’s what people saw. Dick Nixon, the weak-willed man, Dick Nixon, the appeaser, Dick Nixon, the goddamn Red, Good God, for what you did, you should have been—.”

His drink spilling, the president fell suddenly silent. Crouching to pick up the glass not broken, Nixon gazed up, now on his knees.

“I’m sorry, Jack. I didn’t…I didn’t mean it. But you never understood them, the forces in this country, you never could see them. You can’t hold back…”

The president then clambered up, clumsily, never losing eye contact.

“You have to tear them limb from limb, you understand? Gut the bastards, crush the traitors under your heel. Make them scream, make them cry, make them pay.”

“Mr. President—.”

Nixon whirled around. Lieutenant Morgan leaped backwards behind the corner, white as a ghost, Major Anderson barely suppressing his laugh. The Chief of Staff cleared his throat once more, still standing in the doorway down the hall, knuckles tapping the walls.

“Your meeting with the Air Force team regarding the strike on those targets up North, Mr. President. They’re ready to see you now.”

Design for War

“Must have been pretty painful around here.”

Major Anderson took a drink, “You could say that.”

“I mean, Jesus, do you think he ever considered…” Lieutenant Morgan began in hushed tones, leaning forward.

“You mean…?” Major Anderson queried, eyes squinting, before firmly shaking his head. “No, no chance.”

“Once the American people start valuing weakness…losing these masculine ideals, well, then it all goes away. We need strong leaders, tough men…not this, this…forget it…”

The president staggered over to where he left his bottle of brandy on the floor, propped up against the wall, and he began to drink.

“You know what the Chinese word for crisis is? It’s…it’s, well, Christ, the word itself doesn’t matter, but it means ‘danger’ and ‘opportunity.’ Think about that. There’s always a risk, always, heh, always a gamble. But it can pay off, you get it?”

Growing agitated, the president set his drink back down, spilling it over the carpet mindlessly, next to the other stains, but he droned on.

“Ike, the dumb son-of-a-bitch, useless bastard, he never understood it. Never. Back with Hungary, he dithered. Got all that praise, all that war hero crap with the Suez business. MacArthur, now there was a man, a man with real class…you ever meet him? You probably did, during the Cuba business, I bet he told you to, heh, to just drop a bomb on the place, right Jack?”

Kennedy remained silent, his head still bowed down, gaze fixed on the stain Nixon was now treading on, as the president began pouring himself another drink.

“That was your error, your fatal one. You blinked. Not with the Soviets…no, no, no, they didn’t give a damn about some funny little island in the Caribbean. You blinked with the maniacs in the basement, the ones we keep locked up. They smelled blood, they knew you didn’t have it in you, so they bite. You can’t let them do that to you, Jack. I won;t…real leaders don’t. You have to be the one to do it yourself. Truman didn’t wait, did he? Every speech at the funeral praised him for being the one to do it, the one to press the…”

The bottle slipped from Nixon’s grasp again, bouncing off the carpet, spilling brandy all over the floor.

“Mr. President—.”

“No time for that,” Nixon shouted as he whirled around. Lieutenant Morgan leaped backwards behind the corner, white as a ghost, Major Anderson barely suppressing his own horror.

Flustered, the White House Chief of Staff gathered himself before trying to ask again.

“Mr. President, what, what do you mean? The briefing on those strikes in Cambodia, I thought you sai-”

“Fuck ‘em. Cancel it, I don’t give a shit. Get me the Joint Chiefs. Tell them I need to see them here at once, national emergency, give ‘em that crap.”

Nixon marched into the room opposite Jack’s portrait, about to slam the door before stopping to bark one last order at his Chief of Staff.

“Oh and uh, grab that young fellow, the Marine, whatever, the one with the big briefcase upstairs. Bring him down here, I want to speak with him.”

Slamming the door shut, the White House phone lines glowed to life, and Kennedy remained still.

DATE: MAY 1, 1973

FROM: ████████████████████

SUBJECT: THE DEATH OF RICHARD NIXON

NOTES ON THE PASSING OF AN AMERICAN PRESIDENT WHOSE YEARS OF FIERCE REPRESSION AND MALADMINISTRATION HAVE BROUGHT RUIN TO A NATION

WASHINGTON, DC—U.S. service members swear an oath to “support and defend the Constitution against all enemies foreign and domestic.”

On May 1, 1973, the US Department of the Army joined with the American citizens to fulfill this pledge and guarantee the Constitutional processes of the nation. In the early hours of the morning, the US armed forces participated in an operation to retake control of the White House and US Capitol Complex.

The operation brings to an end the despotic reign of Richard M. Nixon, aged 60. Richard Nixon was a former US president and one of the country’s most durable figures. His government was enabled by years of repression and long-simmering national rage. He demanded slavish subservience at home and abroad and engaged in criminal, coercive acts that undermined the country’s sacred democratic processes.

In a memo signed yesterday, the Acting Secretary of the Army joined with other Joint Chiefs in declaring that Nixon’s activities “were inconsistent with the rule of law” and constituted “sedition and insurrection.” It was only after a 24-hour deadline that officials acted to preserve the country’s traditions and values.

The Acting Secretary of the Army honors the bravery of the service men who remained true to their oaths amid this crisis. He extends his heartfelt thanks to the American people, who stood as one to oppose the tyrant whose charges include subversion of the national economy, embezzlement, racketeering, armed attack on the people, destruction of buildings and state institutions, subversion of congressional authority, election interference, and genocide.

In coordination with relevant state authorities, the Acting Secretary is involved in continued operations to restore order and ensure a seamless transfer of power to civilian governance. A variety of individuals have been released from unlawful incarceration—Al Haig, Allard Lowenstein, Alexander Barkan, Charles Dyson, Daniel Schorr, Howard Stein, Hunter Thompson, Leonard Woodcock, Morton Halperin, and Mary McGrory.

Members of the regime—including principal enablers H.R. Haldeman, John Ehrlichman, and John Mitchell—have been detained. They will face prosecution for their misdeeds. We urge every American to lay down their arms. Now is the time not for recriminations but reconciliation.

A brief statement from the Pentagon follows:

“Almost two hundred years ago, the United States planted the tree of liberty. Today, we have refreshed it. From the crucible of this event, our nation will emerge stronger than ever. We will move past this calamity. Our long national nightmare is over.”

The Fatigue Press, December 1972

On Wednesday, November 8, 1972, at approximately 8:00 p.m., First Sergeant Williams and the C.O. entered room 265 of the 397th Signal Company and found its occupant dead in the closet.

Pfc Bruce Dellums was a native of Fresno, California. He was found hanging from a rope from his alert-readiness pack in his locker. From the appearance of his body, it was clear he had been hanging there for at least a day. His disappearance was not noticed because of Election Night hub-bub.

People who knew Bruce say he was in a bad state. He had been relieved of his job as a switchboard operator. He had faced disciplinary action for telling a captain that he’d “frag the guy” if sent to Vietnam. He was hoping for a discharge that never came.

No one knows what exactly drove the guy to do it. All we in The Fatigue Press have are rumors and the few stories that his friends have been willing to tell. The story that emerges is of a guy that had many problems, personal and Army-related. He probably had no business being in the Army at all. But here’s what we know:
1. Bruce had a drinking problem and had wracked up a $400.00 tab at a local bar.
2. He was likely homosexual and had been beaten up by his roommate for making sexual advances.
3. He had briefly been under psychiatric observation, only for the base psychiatrist to diagnose him with mild depression and declare him “fit for duty”.
4. The night before the Election, he told one of his few friends that the “country’s going to hell” and he didn’t think the war would ever really end if “Nixon got his rocks off” as predicted.
The Army’s been all too keen to shove Dellums under the rug, as it has with every other dead kid. They’re all the same to the bosses. Here’s just one more fuck-up. Here’s one more body. Sweep him aside. Slap a flag on him. Throw him in the ground. They don’t care that he suffered. Their idea of an official explanation is a three-sentence story in the backpages of Stars and Stripes. They won’t ask why someone so young felt the world was so hopeless, why he felt so sure that there was no future after this Election, why his one attempt to get help led to Army psychiatrists shooting him up with tranquilizers, why no one even noticed he was gone for hours after he’d hung himself in his locker.

If even the most basic concern had been invested in Bruce, could he have been saved? I don’t know. It’s easy for the bosses to dope people up on pills, to fire them and give them a new job. It’s easy too for them to make someone the object of jokes and abuse.

Bruce was a homosexual and that was funny. He liked to sing and talked funny and that was funny. He committed suicide and that was funny to them too.

Maybe only a few select men in this country are deserving of an honorable death. Maybe the only way to get a lick of respect in this country is to go out like Richard Nixon, by getting elected president and then blowing your brains out all over the Oval Office because of the suffering you’ve inflicted on a million other people.

And if that’s what it takes, this country doesn’t deserve all the sympathy being lavished on it.

We don’t deserve to be a country at all.

May 22, 1973

While Richard Nixon initially succeeded in his efforts to thwart America’s democratic processes, his efforts also sowed the seeds of his defeat. Spurred by the arrests of his political rivals, his declaration of a national emergency, and attempted cancellation of the 1972 presidential election, many brave men and women took to the streets to protest the would-be regime with support from state and local officials. Escalating violence against these protestors—including the shooting of some 80 unarmed youth in LaFayette Plaza—turned increasing numbers of Americans against the Nixon government.

By May 1973, the situation had become untenable for the president and his supporters. As military leaders ceased their efforts to defend Washington and various cabinet members fled for Latin America, the president found himself alone, surrounded by hostile governors and national guard forces. He issued several final broadcasts to the nation over television and radio—though breakdowns in federal telecommunications infrastructure ensured that these messages reached only a handful of public broadcast stations.

The deaths of the Nixon government’s principal actors and the intentional destruction of many tapes, files, and other documents make these broadcasts the clearest record of Richard Nixon’s state in his final days. The US Center for the Second Constitution and the Edward M. Kennedy Memorial Library present these broadcasts in their original format.

Transcripts are available on the nearby wall for the hearing impaired.

Good evening.

My fellow Americans, my fellow citizens,

My Americans.

This is the 49th time I have spoken to you from this office, where so many important decisions have been made. This is the office where Lincoln conducted his war against the Confederacy, where Wilson and Roosevelt fought to preserve our freedom, where John F. Kennedy faced off against the Soviet Union. I have tried to act as they have. I have tried to act as they have to—. To—.

I truly believe… I do believe… I have acted in the national interest. I have acted to preserve the Union from the anarchists, the criminal elements who would tear down our Republic to its foundations. Across the nation there are insurrectionists—. S-subversives. They would extinguish the torch of…

[Rustling of papers]

Let’s put that aside. You’ve heard enough uhh… well-prepared remarks from speechwriters, media men, what have you. But what you haven’t heard—. What you haven’t heard is my own personal reflections on this great crisis that we face.

I am not a sentimental man, but what I tell you now is from the heart. It’s my, my great outpouring. It’s—.

[Chuckling. Rustling of papers.]

As many know, I was raised by a strong Midwestern woman who instilled in me certain qualities. The most important of these is a certain coolness. The… The tougher it gets, the cooler I get. I excel under pressure. Like Lincoln. Like Lincoln over one hundred years ago defended this nation from dissolution and ruin so too… So too… I am stronger than ever… I possess a— a— firmness, the resolve to continue this great battle… A fortitude…

I know it does not seem like it now, but rest assured that we are on the precipice. We are on the precipice of a great victory. The greatest victory in American history. Maybe all mankind. Our enemies don’t understand it, but I do. We both do.

We’ve sacrificed everything for this moment and we won’t go down like the Romanovs. Not like a dog. Never like a dog. On our own terms. We’ve fought too hard for that.

God, if my mother could see…

[Clearing throat]

Rest assured that I am in constant communication with the Joint Chiefs, with our allies, with your governors and representatives. Our armed forces remain as powerful and united as ever. Events in, uhh, Vietnam notwithstanding, we are the greatest military force on earth. We can still come together. We can, as our forefathers did, sacrifice for the greater good.

I call upon all Americans to recognize this, to… compromise and lay down their arms.

For my part, I will carry it through to the finish regardless of whatever personal agony it will involve. I will remain in this Office, as your president, to ensure that the interests of the Nation are upheld. When this violence ends, when this battle is complete, I am confident that we will be able to return to the normal business of government. We will see a restoration of the prosperity which has eluded us for so many years.

We will ensure there is no more pain.

We will achieve peace with honor.

May God’s grace be with you all in the days ahead.

[End of Recording]

May 4, 1977

“When the president does it, that means it is not illegal.”

When former President Richard Nixon said these words to British journalist David Frost in 1977, most Americans saw them as tantamount to a confession of guilt about the Watergate scandal, which had consumed his presidency and drove him from office in disgrace three years prior. But the entire context of these remarks must be read in full to understand the president’s meaning. The questions Frost posed to Mr. Nixon were not in reference to the Watergate burglaries of June 1972 or the subsequent cover-up. They were narrowly focused on the unconstitutional “Huston Plan” of 1970, which proposed giving U.S. intelligence agencies expansive new powers to trample on civil liberties at home, in effect creating a secret police.

This form of lawbreaking by law enforcement was not unique to the Nixon years. J. Edgar Hoover’s FBI epitomized that spirit of total disregard for Americans’ constitutional rights, so long as their dismissal served the aims of a wider ideological war, at the time against communists. The targets shifted somewhat in the Nixon presidency, away from the old left’s Red Guard, and towards the youth-led antiwar movement and its more radical fringes, namely the Weather Underground, which committed numerous acts of senseless violence during the late 60’s and early 70’s.

The most important was perhaps the Greenwich townhouse explosion on March 6, 1970, when the Weather Underground’s amateur bomb-making blew back in their face, killing three of their own cadres and leveling an apartment building. It beggars belief that the United States government was at risk of being overthrown by these wannabe radicals, as Richard Nixon claimed in order to ram through the Huston Plan. The Weather Underground’s worst enemy was itself.

But the target of Nixon’s wrath was never the point. A deeply paranoid and vindictive man, his enemies included schoolboy rivals, New Deal bureaucrats, the Kennedy family, the press, and liberals at large. Watergate or the Huston Plan were not isolated incidents, they were a way of life in the Nixon administration, in which time the country saw the rise of the imperial presidency and its abuse of the vast powers that Cold War intelligence agencies placed in its lap.

With the savage war in Vietnam prolonged for another four years, between 1969 and 1973, the war was brought home, with the types of counterinsurgency tactics first used in the rice paddies of Indochina brought to American streets. In the mid-70’s, the last gasp of these radical groups were decimated in violent battles, like the May 1974 shootout that destroyed the Symbionese Liberation Army. The police officers doing the shooting were largely Vietnam veterans using surplus military hardware to execute the same search-and-destroy operations they had conducted overseas.

The pattern of militarization abroad leading to militarization at home has been a constant of American history. The ubiquitousness of SWAT teams came from Vietnam. Excess military hardware generated for the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan were then distributed to small town cops under the 1033 Program. Expansive powers for immigration enforcement generated at the height of War on Terror hysteria are now being used to imprison dissenters of further American-backed wars abroad.

Richard Nixon hastened the rise of empire at home, and we will all pay the price for the silence of his fiercest critics to seriously challenge the symbiotic relation between Watergate and Vietnam. When Congressman John Conyers (D-MI) introduced an article of impeachment against Richard Nixon—along with the agreed-upon counts of obstruction of justice, abuse of power, and contempt of Congress—for his illegal bombing of Cambodia, in which he lied to the American people and Congress about this war of aggression for years, it was shot down. Nine Democrats broke party lines to join Republicans and defeat the Cambodia amendment, including antiwar bleeding-heart liberals like Peter Rodino. Reflecting on the failed push for Congress to reassert its constitutional war powers, Conyers stated “condemning the Cambodian bombing would also have required us to indict previous administrations and to admit that the Congress has failed to fully meet its own constitutional obligations.”

Put simply, when the president does it, that means it is not illegal.

FROST: You called a meeting on June the fifth, 1970, about the Huston plan and eventually approved it in July. It got your okay on July the fourteenth, didn’t it? And in the Huston plan it stated very clearly, with reference to the entry that was being proposed, it said very clearly, use of this technique is clearly illegal, it amounts to burglary … however, it is also one of the most fruitful tools and it can produce the type of intelligence which cannot be obtained in any other fashion. Why did you approve a plan that included an element like that … that was clearly illegal?

NIXON: Because as president of the United States … ah … I had to make a decision, as has faced most presidents, in fact, all of them, ah … in which, ah … the national security in terms of a threat from abroad, ah … and the security of the individual … individual violence at home had to be put first. Ah … I think Abraham Lincoln has stated it better than anybody else, as he does in so many cases. When he said, “Must a government be too strong for the liberties of its people? Or too weak to defend or maintain its own existence?” That’s the dilemma that presidents have had to face, ah … Roosevelt had to face it in World War II. Truman and Eisenhower in the Cold War period. Kennedy and Johnson as Vietnam began to come in. And Kennedy, of course, even before Vietnam began to escalate, had the beginning of the violent racial disturbances … ah … which led to some activities in this category. Now let’s first, let’s second understand what the surreptitious entry is limited to. You will note that a surreptitious entry in cases involving national security and specifically mentions, ah … two, ah … groups of, ah … internal organizations who had no foreign connections as far as we know. Ah … the Weathermen and the Black Panthers.

Now, why were we concerned? Let’s look at the year, 1970. We had a situation where thirty-five thousand people, ah … had been victims of assaults. A number of them had been killed. It was a year in which we had, ah … sixteen airplane hijackings. There had been about eleven the year before. Ah … but most significantly, it was a year in which there had been thirty thousand bombings and fifty thousand …I mean, sorry, three thousands bombings, three thousand bombings and fifty thousand bomb threats … which caused, ah … the evacuation of buildings. Ah… it was a year of turbulence in American society. Ah … ’‘68 … ’69 … ’70 … the residue of the terrible period of ’68. Washing over into ’69 and continued through ’70 and then, thank God, began to go down in ’71 and ’72, when calm was restored to the campuses. The cities did cease to be burned, and bombings did go down. And while we’ve argued about our crime statistics, where at least in ’72 there was a decrease rather than an increase. Alright, now, now in 1970, in the middle of 1970, ah … we were faced with a situation here, first, where the intelligence agencies weren’t working together. Ah … there were CIA … was not speaking to the FBI … the NSA, the National Security Agency, which of course does all of our [cryptographic] work. That’s the highly sensitive, technical work, you know, to break codes and that sort of thing … had very little communication with the other two. Ah … under the circumstances I felt that we had to coordinate these activities and get a more effective program for dealing with, first, foreign-directed, ah … espionage, ah … or foreign-supported, ah… subversion. And in addition with domestic groups that used and advocated violence… .

FROST: So, what in a sense you’re saying is that there are certain situations and the Huston plan or that part of it was one of them where the president can decide that it’s in the best interest of the nation or something and do something illegal.

NIXON: Well, when the president does it … that means that it is not illegal.

FROST: By definition –

NIXON: Exactly … exactly… if the president … if, for example, the president approves something … approves an action, ah … because of the national security or in this case because of a threat to internal peace and order of, ah … ah … significant magnitude … then … the president’s decision in that instance is one, ah … that enables those who carry it out to carry it out without violating a law. NIXON: Well … I think that we would … I think that we’re splitting hairs here. Burglaries per se are illegal. Let’s begin with that proposition. That’s the way I would put it. Now, that isn’t trying to split hairs … but I do not mean to suggest the president is above the law … what I am suggesting, however, what we have to understand, is, in wartime particularly, war abroad, and virtually revolution in certain concentrated areas at home, that a president does have under the Constitution extraordinary powers and must exert them with … as little as possible. . . . `); e.executable.push([2, () => { e.image = 'https://i.imgur.com/XDF7s80.png '; }]); } else if (out == "win" && dem == 5 ) {//win + jackson e.pages.push(`

March 21, 1973

On October 6, 1973, at 2:00pm Cairo time, Egypt and Syria’s militaries launched a coordinated assault on Israeli forces in the Golan Heights and the Sinai. While the attack came as a shock to Israeli intelligence and the world at large, it was not entirely unanticipated, as this series in the National Security Archive’s retrospective on the conflict shows.

Notably, these diplomatic preparations for the outbreak of conflict in the Middle East excluded regional partners, and were carried out through what Nixon and Kissinger liked to call “shuttle diplomacy” in his first term. But since re-election, Nixon largely neglected that tactic, instead preferring decisive military action.

The Middle East was one area where this was not true, where President Nixon still deferred to private diplomacy conducted by informal “mediators” behind closed door, as the actions by William Simon in late 1973 and early 1974 demonstrate. January 3, 1974

In 1972, Richard Nixon prevailed against George Wallace in that year’s presidential election. This victory generated questions among power brokers in both parties about the kind of messages they wanted to advance and the voting groups they needed to appeal to. While clashes between pro- and anti-integrationist candidates defined the Democratic Party’s struggles through the 1970s, a very different conversation was taking place in Republican circles. This recording of a conversation between President Richard Nixon, FBI Director Gray, and White House Advisor John Ehrlichman from January 1974 reflects the tenor of these discussions and the White House’s approach to growing instances of political violence across the shifting South.

NIXON: —has to do with national security. They’re a hell of a lot of people, these violent groups.

January 17, 1975

Following his stunning electoral defeat in 1972, Richard Nixon’s post-presidency was a jarring change of pace in his daily routine, and a gutting blow to his fragile ego. Launching into deep depression the minute he boarded Marine One and left office on January 20, 1973, the president was inconsolable for months, and demanded the same aides who had worked with him in the White House follow him home.

In this time, H.R. Haldeman began nurturing an idea to reconstruct the Oval Office in Key Biscayne, Florida. Initially pushing it out of his head, it wasn’t until Summer ‘74 when Haldeman acted, hiring a construction firm to create an exact replica of Nixon’s former workplace, inside his own home. Once it was complete, the former president rarely left, falling asleep at his desk or on couches inside the faux Oval Office. He insisted on referring to his former advisors by their titles, and wanted to be briefed as if he were still president.

The office was an exact duplicate of the one Richard Nixon had inhabited for four years, right down to the voice-activated taping system, which remained online. These tapes can be found at the University of Southern California, under the Jane Fonda Presidential Library and Museum. The transcript below is an excerpt from the Key Biscayne recording on January 17, 1975. After his presidency, Richard Nixon returned to San Clemente, California, where he kept his papers and archival materials. August 8, 1975

On August 8, 1975, the novelist Mary McCarthy interviewed Richard Nixon as part of research for a collection of essays she was drafting on the state of American politics. It, along with all other interviews with the former president, is made by the National Archives and Records Administration and the Center for the Study of the Nixon Presidency. MCCARTHY: A few toes as well.

MCCARTHY: I wonder if I might ask you about your recent divorce and the allegations of abuse from P—.

NIXON: This interview is over.

August 6, 1974

John Connally’s ascent to the presidency was expected in some ways and unexpected in many others. The former Texas governor had long enjoyed a status as a political maverick, an accomplished statesman, and survivor of political violence. Still, ascending to the presidency in the aftermath of the failed Nixon Administration—amid broad popular discontent, with a hostile Congress, presented severe challenges. In place of the honeymoon period that many of his predecessors enjoyed, Connally entered office more disliked than liked, with Gallup finding only 39% of Americans approving of his leadership.

Matters worsened for the Connally Administration in 1974 after the New York Times and Washington Post published a series of stories alleging that the President had a long history of corrupt conduct. Encouraged by significant gains in the House and Senate in that year’s midterms, House liberals successfully impeached Connally.

As matters spiralled out of the president’s control, he turned to former president Richard Nixon for guidance. September 29, 1973

After Richard Nixon’s resignation in 1972, Nelson Rockefeller was elevated to the role of President of the United States, inheriting an election race thrown into chaos, an overheated economy, and a war still raging in Vietnam. With Edward M. Kennedy’s confidence shattered, his presidential campaign floundered in the wake of Rockefeller’s immediate popularity, giving Republicans another term in the White House.

Given that Kennedy was widely seen as the Democrats’ best chance to retake the presidency, the party was wracked with doubt about their ability to win elections, let alone their competence to govern. With the 1974 midterms approaching, many liberals sought to exploit emerging cracks in the Republican coalition, appealing to populist instincts instead of their usual constituencies. Rockefeller was always somewhat out of place in the party culturally, with his elite ivy tower status seen as an anchor around his neck in times where working Americans had to tighten their belts. In 1973, the president committed an infamous gaffe, in which he misheard a reporters’ question on “a pause in higher interest rates” as a question about Applause, the Tony Award winning Broadway musical starring Lauren Bacall.

The transcript below captures Rockefeller’s reaction at the press conference to his mistake, along with other questions on the important issues of the day:

Q: Mr. President, any comment on the latest moves from the Chilean military junta’s defense of the coup? Foreign Minister Ismael Huerta told the General Assembly at the U.N. today that he’s been the victim of a smear campaign.

ROCKEFELLER: Oh, well, I-I wouldn’t say anything that would give, ah, Secretary Armstrong any heartburn here, so I’ll, ah, refrain from any comments on the-the business down South. But it’s a marvelous country, and well, heh, the United Nations, my Goodness, what a marvelous building. January 15, 1974

The Miller Center’s Presidency Project is committed to declassification of White House records which can shed light on significant events in American history. One such event was what one scholar called “the last known act of official anti-Semitism conducted by the United States government.” Beginning in 1971, President Richard Nixon demanded aides provide him a list of officials in the Bureau of Labor Statistics with “Jewish-sounding names.” Thirteen government employees were named, and Nixon fired all of them, fuming to advisors about how jobs reports were being “cooked” by them.

These bigoted rants and acts of antisemitism coming from the highest official in U.S. government are a dark note in the history of the presidency, but we at the Miller Center believe it is important to preserve these materials, in order for future generations to learn the unvarnished truth about their country’s leaders. Which is why we have a petition on our website to call for the repeal of S.B. 272, demanding school textbooks be rewritten to excise chapters of American history like slavery, ethnic cleansing of Native Americans, and the Cambodian genocide.

The excerpt below comes from a tape recorded on January 15, 1974, during a meeting where Nixon was briefed on developments in the Middle East peace process.

NIXON: You know, Colby was telling me the other day, that as a boy you’re taught to never, lie, cheat, or steal. But when he got to the CIA, Christ, he told me all he ever does is lie, cheat, and steal.

[LAUGHTER]

NIXON: Could go for all of government, incidentally. That reminds me, Malek, what have you got on that list I heard about?

MALEK: Thank you, sir. I know the Labor Department reports on inflation have been, frankly, treasonous.

NIXON: Damn right.

MALEK: I also know there are a lot of, er, what you would call enemies in government, who are trying to thwart your movement. The Watergate hoax, the meat boycott panic last year, and now this inflation scam—

SIMON: Well, hold on, the report from—

NIXON: No, no, let him finish. Go on, Fred.

MALEK: And when you first gave me that assignment in 1971, I remember clearly you told me to root out the traitors in government, and I thank you for that mandate sir, but the thirteen [Bureau of Labor Statistics] officials we fired were only scratching the surface.

NIXON: Absolutely. They’re goddamn everywhere.

MALEK: So in preparation for this briefing, I’ve computerized an enormous database of every government employee with, as you said, uh, as you told me, anyone with a Jewish-sounding name.

NIXON: Thank God.

MALEK: I know this may be a step some will bristle at, rounding up Jews and putting their names on lists and all—

NIXON: You really put all of their names in that file there?

MALEK: —but I believe it’s the most effective way to preserve your mandate, as you told me.

NIXON: That’s incredible. Christ. Look at this, over in the State Department. Good God, there’s thousands of them.

SIMON: I think we’re, uh, getting a little sidetracked here. I’m not sure how firing every Jew in government is relevant to the briefing I’ve been giving the president on the Arab oil embargo…

MALEK: You never understood the threat we faced, William. You’re busy shuttling off to—

SIMON: That’s way out of line, what the hell are—

MALEK: —God knows where, meanwhile the president is being cornered from all sides—

SIMON: —you talking about? This is insanity, you sound like a fucking mental patient at a bus station—

MALEK: —from the enemy within and you want him to back down now? You’re nothing but—

NIXON: Wait a minute, Henry’s in here?

MALEK: Oh. Uh, yes, sir. There were bound to be a few high level officials included in the, ah, list. It was computer-generated, so I couldn’t filter out the—

NIXON: No, no, that’s good.

MALEK: Oh.

NIXON: He’s been a real pain in the ass with this embargo, constantly side-stepping Bill and the others, maybe he ought to leave…

SIMON: Mr. President, with respect, it is the height of insanity to fire your Secretary of State in the middle of an international crisis on the advice of a fucking computer and a junior aide not fit to polish your shoes when—

MALEK: Do you want the president to fight this threat or not? Answer the question!

NIXON: Fred, Bill, calm the hell down. Christ, no wonder the Democrats are beating us on this goddamn Watergate nonsense if you’re all at each other’s throats. Even Chisholm is scoring on us now. Focus on the real enemy at hand: mid-level BLS statisticians reporting minor increases in inflation every month.

MALEK: Of course, I’m sorry sir.

NIXON: It’s fine, Fred, I know you’re busy on Bush’s staff. Also have you gotten word on if that McCain kid is going to run for the open seat in that, uh, what was it? Arizona district?

MALEK: Thanks, Mr. President. And no, sir, he hasn’t made a final decision yet, but we believe if he does, he’ll be a terrific ally.

NIXON: That’s great…Christ, this list is incredible.

MALEK: It took a lot of time.

NIXON: If only we had one for the goddamn press, all those pollsters saying our approval is in the teens. What the fuck does that even mean?

MALEK: I don’t know, sir. But…I suppose I can get right on it.

NIXON: Can you add other ethnicities while you’re at it? This bastard in Commerce was giving me a hard time the other day, he’s not Jewish, but he’s Italian. See if you can come up with that list too.

MALEK: Sure.

April 3, 1973

After Eugene McCarthy’s underdog campaign shocked the world with his victory in 1972, Richard Nixon for many weeks refused to acknowledge his loss, and insisted on continuing the formalities presidents are accustomed to in their time in office. When McCarthy’s team moved into the White House in January ‘73, Nixon fled to South Florida, where he often spoke over the phone with Republican Party leaders, titans of industry, and heads of state. In April of 1973, as McCarthy’s withdrawal plans for Vietnam were rapidly accelerating, a frantic Richard Nixon phoned one of his allies inside the Beltway to ask how this could have happened.

NIXON: Christ, I just don’t understand it. Whenever Henry and I did anything that pissed off those bastards, even the most minute things, they’d blow their tops. A single arms shipment has one goddamn delay and the whole clique at Foreign Affairs loses their damned minds. It’s unbelievable.
